            <title><![CDATA[Games We Want On Switch 2, Hands-On With Assassin's Creed Shadows, And More Of The Week's Takes]]></title>
            <link>https://kotaku.com/switch-2-games-we-want-assassins-creed-shadows-preview-1851747334</link>
            <guid>https://www.resetera.com/threads/games-we-want-on-switch-2-hands-on-with-assassins-creed-shadows-and-more-of-the-weeks-takes.1092204/</guid>
            <content:encoded><![CDATA[https://kotaku.com/switch-2-games-we-want-assassins-creed-shadows-preview-1851747334<br/><br/><div id="readability-page-1" class="page"><div><div><figure id="" data-id="836d61176b56a7344eae46c786fa6658" data-recommend-id="image://836d61176b56a7344eae46c786fa6658" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="false" data-imagerights="in-house-art" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Blizzard Entertainment / Nintendo / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Ubisoft<!-- -->, <!-- -->Nintendo / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Lucasfilm / Aspyr<!-- -->, <!-- -->The Pokémon Company / Kotaku<!-- -->, <!-- -->Sandfall Interactive<!-- -->, <!-- -->FromSoftware / Bandai Namco<!-- -->, <!-- -->Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Amiga Power<!-- -->, <!-- -->S-Game</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="836d61176b56a7344eae46c786fa6658" data-recommend-id="image://836d61176b56a7344eae46c786fa6658" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>There was no shortage of things for us to have opinions on this week. First, we shared our picks for the games we most want to see make their way to the Nintendo Switch 2. We also shared our impressions of <em>Assassin’s Creed Shadows </em>after some recent hands-on time with the game, and look ahead to what seems to be a pretty promising year for Xbox Game Pass. Read on for these takes and more.</p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="b0e671bb3cd9f65e797f21411cca6490" data-recommend-id="image://b0e671bb3cd9f65e797f21411cca6490" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Lilith from Diablo is shown inside a Switch 2 screen." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="Lilith from Diablo is shown inside a Switch 2 screen." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Blizzard Entertainment / Nintendo / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="b0e671bb3cd9f65e797f21411cca6490" data-recommend-id="image://b0e671bb3cd9f65e797f21411cca6490" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Lilith from Diablo is shown inside a Switch 2 screen." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>The original Switch was a trailblazing device that proved you could take console-quality games on the go, but it was demonstrably less powerful than its PlayStation and Xbox competitors. In the years since the Switch was released, that gap has only grown with the release of the PS5 and Xbox Series X/S. We still don’t have official specs for the Switch 2, but it will likely be a decent leap forward for Nintendo’s line of handheld/console hybrids. As such, it wouldn’t be too surprising to see some older games make their way to the device that couldn’t feasibly run on the original, so we got to thinking about some big games that we’d like to see ported to the Switch 2. Here are a few of our ideas.  - Kenneth Shepard <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/nintendo-switch-2-games-elden-ring-gtav-final-fantasy-1851745512&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/nintendo-switch-2-games-elden-ring-gtav-final-fantasy-1851745512">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="6514a2accdf6c3bdbbb1c46b207217d0" data-recommend-id="image://6514a2accdf6c3bdbbb1c46b207217d0" data-format="jpg" data-width="1150" data-height="647" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="The image of the Four Cyclists of the Apocalypse in the final issue of AMIGA POWER." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="The image of the Four Cyclists of the Apocalypse in the final issue of AMIGA POWER." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="fair-use" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->Amiga Power</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="6514a2accdf6c3bdbbb1c46b207217d0" data-recommend-id="image://6514a2accdf6c3bdbbb1c46b207217d0" data-format="jpg" data-width="1150" data-height="647" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="The image of the Four Cyclists of the Apocalypse in the final issue of AMIGA POWER." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>There is a reasonable chance you have not heard of Jonathan Nash. However, the games journalist and comedy writer has been such an inspiration for a generation of games critics, and the generation inspired by them, that his influence has almost certainly reached you. J Nash was extraordinary, and I’m very sorry to report he has died. I also can’t wait to tell you why you will want to read everything he ever wrote. - John Walker <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/jonathan-nash-games-critic-amiga-power-obituary-1851745081&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/jonathan-nash-games-critic-amiga-power-obituary-1851745081">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="c64e33a9ac114b18638a5628054899cc" data-recommend-id="image://c64e33a9ac114b18638a5628054899cc" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="false" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Ubisoft</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="c64e33a9ac114b18638a5628054899cc" data-recommend-id="image://c64e33a9ac114b18638a5628054899cc" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Earlier this month, I got to try out <em>Assassin’s Creed Shadows</em> via a livestreamed four-hour preview. Just a week before that preview, Ubisoft had announced that the next main entry in the open-world franchise about <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/running-around-during-loading-screens-is-an-important-p-1844170039&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/running-around-during-loading-screens-is-an-important-p-1844170039">sneaky assassins</a></span> and evil Templars <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/ubisoft-assassins-creed-shadows-delay-march-february-1851736266&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/ubisoft-assassins-creed-shadows-delay-march-february-1851736266">had been delayed. Again</a></span>. - Zack Zwiezen <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/assassins-creed-shadows-4-hour-preview-hands-on-review-1851745403&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/assassins-creed-shadows-4-hour-preview-hands-on-review-1851745403">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="df6088c92d94ab13a4bfcb8cff8837bc" data-recommend-id="image://df6088c92d94ab13a4bfcb8cff8837bc" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A mock-up of a Mario Kart RPG box cover." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A mock-up of a Mario Kart RPG box cover." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Nintendo / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="df6088c92d94ab13a4bfcb8cff8837bc" data-recommend-id="image://df6088c92d94ab13a4bfcb8cff8837bc" data-format="jpg" data-width="1280" data-height="720" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A mock-up of a Mario Kart RPG box cover." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Nintendo made an interesting decision with <em>Mario Kart 8</em>. They chose to make it so good, and so comprehensive, that it removed the need to make any more. It has now been over ten years since <em>Mario Kart 8</em> first released, more than double the length that’s ever come between an entry in the series before. Honestly, they could re-re-release <em>8</em> for the Switch 2, and it’d still sell millions. Given this, here’s an idea: why not do something <em>dramatically </em>different with <em>Mario Kart 9</em>? - John Walker <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/mario-kart-9-switch-2-rpg-best-argument-all-time-1851743253&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/mario-kart-9-switch-2-rpg-best-argument-all-time-1851743253">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="9ddde70cabe8f5db3aca09996d9be9a3" data-recommend-id="image://9ddde70cabe8f5db3aca09996d9be9a3" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Lucasfilm / Aspyr</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="9ddde70cabe8f5db3aca09996d9be9a3" data-recommend-id="image://9ddde70cabe8f5db3aca09996d9be9a3" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>Here’s an interesting question: If the subject of a really good remaster is a bad game, does that mean the remaster is also bad, or just a good way to experience the original flawed product? That’s the question I’ve been pondering since playing <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/games/star-wars-episode-i-jedi-power-battles?_gl=1*562dhj*_ga*MTM0Mjk0ODIxMC4xNjkxNzY3NjQ2*_ga_V4QNJTT5L0*MTczNzY2NTEyNy4xMDguMS4xNzM3NjY1NTMyLjYwLjAuMA..&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/games/star-wars-episode-i-jedi-power-battles?_gl=1*562dhj*_ga*MTM0Mjk0ODIxMC4xNjkxNzY3NjQ2*_ga_V4QNJTT5L0*MTczNzY2NTEyNy4xMDguMS4xNzM3NjY1NTMyLjYwLjAuMA.."><em>Star Wars: Episode 1: Jedi Power Battles</em></a></span><em>.</em> - Zack Zwiezen <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/star-wars-jedi-power-battles-episode-1-remaster-review-1851746178&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/star-wars-jedi-power-battles-episode-1-remaster-review-1851746178">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="1d164045d60a606fb6112468cd815e36" data-recommend-id="image://1d164045d60a606fb6112468cd815e36" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="The three pack arts for Genetic Apex." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="The three pack arts for Genetic Apex." data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->The Pokémon Company / Kotaku</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="1d164045d60a606fb6112468cd815e36" data-recommend-id="image://1d164045d60a606fb6112468cd815e36" data-format="jpg" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="The three pack arts for Genetic Apex." data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>As we’ve extensively covered, <em>Pokémon TCG Pocket</em> is a lovely mobile card game version of the 30-year-0ld trading card game, but also <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/pokemon-tcg-pocket-gacha-loot-box-gambling-1851690838?_gl=1*z3q71g*_ga*MzQzNjkwNDM2LjE2NDY2NjQ1NzQ.*_ga_V4QNJTT5L0*MTczNzQ5NjY0MC4zMTEuMS4xNzM3NDk2OTI5LjU2LjAuMA..&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/pokemon-tcg-pocket-gacha-loot-box-gambling-1851690838?_gl=1*z3q71g*_ga*MzQzNjkwNDM2LjE2NDY2NjQ1NzQ.*_ga_V4QNJTT5L0*MTczNzQ5NjY0MC4zMTEuMS4xNzM3NDk2OTI5LjU2LjAuMA..">a wide-open doorway to gambling mechanics</a></span>. It’s shocking to realize, early on in your time with the game, that it lets you pour as much as 720 Poké Gold a day into opening new packs, meaning it only cuts players off at roughly $105. Per day. Which is how much one Japanese player has been spending as he celebrates acquiring his 50,000th card. - John Walker <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/pokemon-tcg-pocket-poke-gold-price-1851744809&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/pokemon-tcg-pocket-poke-gold-price-1851744809">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="b49865e5e53d1e5879246ecff16a7f20" data-recommend-id="image://b49865e5e53d1e5879246ecff16a7f20" data-format="png" data-width="1313" data-height="738" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Travelers look at a goddess in the heavens. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="Travelers look at a goddess in the heavens. " data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->Sandfall Interactive</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="b49865e5e53d1e5879246ecff16a7f20" data-recommend-id="image://b49865e5e53d1e5879246ecff16a7f20" data-format="png" data-width="1313" data-height="738" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="Travelers look at a goddess in the heavens. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>While Xbox Game Pass rarely goes a month without getting at least something new that’s worth checking out, it’s certainly <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/xbox-game-pass-subscriber-numbers-2022-xbox-series-x-s-1848963643&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/xbox-game-pass-subscriber-numbers-2022-xbox-series-x-s-1848963643" target="_blank">had its dry spells</a></span> in recent years. The back half of January, however, has quietly revealed a surprising number of cool new games hitting the Netflix-like subscription service, and with several more day-and-date releases announced during <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/xbox-developer-direct-doom-dark-ages-ninja-gaiden-1851746052&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/xbox-developer-direct-doom-dark-ages-ninja-gaiden-1851746052">Thursday’s Xbox Developer Direct</a></span>, 2025 is looking like it might be one of the service’s best years yet. - Ethan Gach <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/game-pass-2025-new-releases-doom-fable-ninja-gaiden-1851746651&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/game-pass-2025-new-releases-doom-fable-ninja-gaiden-1851746651">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="4deb7cca6873fd42f5bac83d5fb15959" data-recommend-id="image://4deb7cca6873fd42f5bac83d5fb15959" data-format="jpg" data-width="1000" data-height="563" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A knight fights a demon in Elden Ring. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A knight fights a demon in Elden Ring. " data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Image<!-- -->: <!-- -->FromSoftware / Bandai Namco</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="4deb7cca6873fd42f5bac83d5fb15959" data-recommend-id="image://4deb7cca6873fd42f5bac83d5fb15959" data-format="jpg" data-width="1000" data-height="563" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A knight fights a demon in Elden Ring. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>One of the biggest developments in gaming isn’t just the growing number of games to play, with thousands more being released every year, but how sticky the biggest blockbusters are, monopolizing players’ money and attention long after they’ve come out. And not just live-service multiplayer games either. New sales data shows how over a third of 2024's best selling games, like <em>Elden Ring</em>, came out years ago.  - Ethan Gach <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/best-selling-games-2024-hogwarts-legacy-dragon-ball-1851746095&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/best-selling-games-2024-hogwarts-legacy-dragon-ball-1851746095">Read More</a></span></p></div><div><figure id="" data-id="2d2584e3f5dcf7b48e3be8103b8b1d64" data-recommend-id="image://2d2584e3f5dcf7b48e3be8103b8b1d64" data-format="jpg" data-width="2000" data-height="1125" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A warrior hides behind his straw hat. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false" contenteditable="false" draggable="false"><div contenteditable="false" data-alt="A warrior hides behind his straw hat. " data-link-reference="" data-link-target="" data-syndicationrights="true" data-imagerights="other-license" data-hide="false" data-hidecredit="false"><p><figcaption>Screenshot<!-- -->: <!-- -->S-Game</figcaption></p></div><span data-id="2d2584e3f5dcf7b48e3be8103b8b1d64" data-recommend-id="image://2d2584e3f5dcf7b48e3be8103b8b1d64" data-format="jpg" data-width="2000" data-height="1125" data-lightbox="false" data-alt="A warrior hides behind his straw hat. " data-recommended="false" data-hide="false"></span></figure><p>  <em>Phantom Blade Zero</em> <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/phantom-blade-0-bloodborne-2-souls-like-fromsoftare-ps5-1850471900&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/phantom-blade-0-bloodborne-2-souls-like-fromsoftare-ps5-1850471900">was first revealed back at Sony’s 2023 gaming showcase</a></span>. At the time, the Chinese-made PlayStation 5 exclusive looked like another project heavily inspired by FromSoftware’s Soulsborne games. But <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/tokyo-game-show-2024-monster-hunter-wilds-mgs-3-remake-1851661898/slides/10&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/tokyo-game-show-2024-monster-hunter-wilds-mgs-3-remake-1851661898/slides/10">playable demos last year</a></span> revealed it’s much closer to a <em>Ninja Gaiden</em> or <em>Devil May Cry</em>-style action game. A new six-minute trailer shows exactly why, and gives the vibe that <em>Phantom Blade 0</em> could be the next <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;External link&quot;,&quot;https://eneba-games.sjv.io/c/379647/1569226/18251?subId1=KT-&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.eneba.com%2Fus%2Fsteam-black-myth-wukong-pc-steam-key-global%3Fenb_campaign%3DMain%2520Search%26enb_content%3Dsearch%2520dropdown%2520-%2520products%26enb_medium%3Dproduct%2520card%26enb_source%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.eneba.com%252F%26enb_term%3D1&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://eneba-games.sjv.io/c/379647/1569226/18251?subId1=KT-&amp;u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.eneba.com%2Fus%2Fsteam-black-myth-wukong-pc-steam-key-global%3Fenb_campaign%3DMain%2520Search%26enb_content%3Dsearch%2520dropdown%2520-%2520products%26enb_medium%3Dproduct%2520card%26enb_source%3Dhttps%253A%252F%252Fwww.eneba.com%252F%26enb_term%3D1" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><em>Black Myth: Wukong</em></a></span><em>. </em> - Ethan Gach <span><a data-ga="[[&quot;Embedded Url&quot;,&quot;Internal link&quot;,&quot;https://kotaku.com/phantom-blade-zero-boss-fight-trailer-release-date-ps5-1851744823&quot;,{&quot;metric25&quot;:1}]]" href="https://kotaku.com/phantom-blade-zero-boss-fight-trailer-release-date-ps5-1851744823">Read More</a></span></p></div></div></div>]]></content:encoded>
